list.content:
The function $f$ is defined by

$$
\begin{aligned}
f(x) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
4x-1 &\text{if}&  x \geq 1, \\[6pt]
-x^2+x+3  &\text{if}&  x<1.
\end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
$$


- Determine whether or not $f$ is continuous at $x = 1$. [2]


The graph of the function $g$ is obtained by applying the following
transformations
to the graph of $f$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\hspace{-5em}\text{a horizontal translation $2$ units to the left, followed by}\\[6pt]
&\hspace{-5em}\text{a reflection in the $x$-axis, followed by}\\[6pt]
&\hspace{-5em}\text{a vertical stretch by a factor of $3$.}
\end{aligned}
$$


- Find $g(x)$.   [4]

list.markScheme:
- We have

  $$

  \begin{array}{rcl}
  \hspace{0.8em} f(1) &=& 4(1)-1 \\[6pt]
  &=& 3
  \end{array}
  $$

  and

  $$
  \begin{array}{rcl}
  \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^-} f(x) &=& -1^2 + 1 + 3 \\[6pt]
  &=& 3 \\[6pt]
  \end{array}
  $$

  Hence
$\answer{\text{\(f\) is continuous at \(x = 1\)}}$
- If we translate the graph of $y = f(x)$ horizontally $2$ units to
the left, we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{1.5em} f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  4x+7      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  -(x+2)^2+x+5  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  If we reflect the graph of
$y = f(x+2)$ in the $x$-axis, we obtain

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  -f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  -4x-7      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  (x+2)^2-x-5  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  If we stretch the graph of
$y = -f(x+2)$ vertically by a factor of $3$, we find

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{1.1em} -3f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  -12x-21      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  3(x+2)^2-3x-15  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence the function $g$ is defined
by

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{4.3em} \answer{g(x) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  -12x-21      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  3(x+2)^2-3x-15  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.}\end{aligned}
  $$

- By considering the differences between the functions we can work out the transformations needed to map $f(x)$ to $g(x)$.
  First we notice that the inner functions are different.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f(x)=2\cos\left(x\textcolor{blue}{\,-\,\frac{\pi}{2}}\right)+3\\[6pt]
  g(x)=4\cos\left(x\textcolor{blue}{\,+\,\frac{\pi}{2}}\right)+2
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  If we add $\pi$ units to the inner function of $f(x)$, it will equal the inner function of  $g(x)$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f(x+\pi)&=2\cos\left(x-\frac{\pi}{2}+\pi\right)+3\\[6pt]
  f(x+\pi)&=2\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+3
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Comparing the function $f(x+\pi)$ to $g(x)$, we notice that the coefficient of cosine has been doubled.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f(x+\pi)=\textcolor{green}{2}\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+3\\[6pt]
  g(x)=\textcolor{green}{4}\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  Hence, if we multiply $f(x+\pi)$ by $2$ we would have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  2f(x+\pi)=2(2\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+3)\\[6pt]
  2f(x+\pi)=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+6
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  If we continue comparing the function $2f(x+\pi)$ to $g(x)$, we see there is a difference of $4$ units.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  2f(x+\pi)&=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\textcolor{red}{\,+\,6}\\[6pt]
  g(x)&=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\textcolor{red}{\,+\,2}
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  Hence, if we apply a vertical shift of $-4$ to $2f(x+\pi)$, we will obtain $g(x)$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  2f(x+\pi)-4&=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+6-4\\[6pt]
  &=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2\\[6pt]
  &=g(x)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Summarising the $3$ transformations, there is
  a horizontal shift $\textbf{left}$ of $\pi$ units, followed by a vertical stretch by a scale factor of $2$ , followed by a vertical shift of $-4$ units.
  Note: The horizontal shift could also come after the vertical transformations, however the two vertical transformations must be applied in the order given.
- In order to apply a vertical translation such that $g(x)>0$ for all $x$, we need to know the minimum value of $g(x)$.
  The minimum value of cosine is $-1$. Hence we can determine the minimum of $g(x)$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
      g(x)&=4\cos\left(x+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)+2\\[6pt]
      &=4(-1)+2\\[6pt]
      &=-2
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence, we need to translate the graph vertically upwards at least $2$ units.
  Therefore, the minimum value is $\answer{k=2}$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- Applying a translation of $a$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis to a function $f$ is shown as $f(x+a)$, and a translation of $b$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis is shown as $f(x)-b$.
  Therefore a translation of $\dfrac{\pi}{3}$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis would be $f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)$. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)+\dfrac{9}{2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Given that $A < \dfrac{9}{2}$, if we then apply a translation of $\dfrac{9}{2} - A$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) - \bigg(\dfrac{9}{2} - A\bigg) &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)+\dfrac{9}{2} - \bigg(\dfrac{9}{2} - A\bigg) \\[10pt]
  &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) + A \\[10pt]
  &= g(x)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore we have the following transformations in any order

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  T_1 &: \hspace{0.5em}\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\text{translation of $\dfrac{\pi}{3}$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis}} \\[10pt]
  T_2 &: \hspace{0.5em}\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\text{translation of $\dfrac{9}{2} - A$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We have $g(0)=\dfrac{9}{2}$. Solving for $A$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  3\cos\left(0+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+A &= \dfrac{9}{2} \\[10pt]
  3\left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right) + A & = \dfrac{9}{2} \\[10pt]
  A & = 3 \\[-12pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore $g(x)=3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+3$ , and the following inequalities hold:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  -1\leq \cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right) &\leq 1 \\[10pt]
  -3\leq 3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right) &\leq 3 \\[10pt]
  0\leq 3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+3 &\leq 6 \\[10pt]
  0\leq g(x) &\leq 6 \\[-12pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore the range of $g$ is $\answer{0\leq g(x) \leq 6}$

- 
  - To find the value of $a$, which is known as the amplitude, we must find half of the vertical distance between the maximum and minimum values.
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/697d6ed2-4137-494f-ada6-07cd489eefc7/images/a928181a-4fcd-4ea9-b71e-dc8f5cea02c9/AA1154a.JPEG)


    We can see from the diagram that the curve is a reflection of $\sin{x}$ in the $x-$axis, therefore the value of $a$ must be negative.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Therefore

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        a&=-\frac{3-(-1)}{2}\\[6pt]
        &=\hspace{0.525em}\answer{-2}  \tag*{\textbf{R1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - To find the  value of $c$ we must find the $y-$value half way between the maximum and minimum values.
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/697d6ed2-4137-494f-ada6-07cd489eefc7/images/f6143e17-9146-4ce4-9c33-b01bced64c56/AA1154b.JPEG)


    Therefore

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        c&=\frac{3+(-1)}{2}\\[6pt]
        &=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{1}  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - To find $b$ we use the formula $T=\frac{2\pi}{b}$.
    We can use the diagram to find $T$ and see that $\frac{T}{2}$ is the $x-$distance between the maximum and minimum values.
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/697d6ed2-4137-494f-ada6-07cd489eefc7/images/c7dc5b6a-813a-4ffb-bafd-b8fb49ff2f45/AA1154c%20(1).JPEG)


    Hence

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \frac{T}{2}&=\left(\tfrac{\pi}{2}-\tfrac{\pi}{6}\right)\\[6pt]
        T&=2\left(\tfrac{\pi}{2}-\tfrac{\pi}{6}\right)\\[6pt]
        T&=\frac{2\pi}{3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Using this value of $T$ and the formula stated above we can find $b$.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \frac{2\pi}{3}&=\frac{2\pi}{b}\\[6pt]
        b&=\hspace{0.525em}\answer{3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$


- For an inverse to exist the function must be one-to-one, this means it must pass the horizontal line test. We can see this is satisfied by the red part of $f(x)$  shown below

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/697d6ed2-4137-494f-ada6-07cd489eefc7/images/2b4f5cbc-7374-4bd7-a0b3-ee6657792bc7/AA1154inv.JPEG)


  We can see that if we add one complete time period to $\tfrac{\pi}{6}$ we will get $k$, hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	k&=\tfrac{\pi}{6}+\tfrac{2\pi}{3}\\[6pt]
  	&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\tfrac{5\pi}{6}}  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- First we split the vertical and horizontal transformations.
  The inner function of $f$ is the horizontal transformations and everything else is vertical.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  	&-2f(\tfrac{1}{2}x)+3\\[6pt]
  	&\text{Vertical}& \hspace{1em} & \text{Horizontal}\\[6pt]
  	&\times -2 & \hspace{1em} & \div 2\\[6pt]
  	&+3 & \hspace{1em} &
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Lets do the vertical transformations first. We don't need to transform the entire function. It is easier to identify a single point and transform that.
  Notice that we are multiplying by a negative number, that means $g$ will be a vertical reflection of $f$.
  Therefore the first maximum point of $g$ will be the image of the transformation of the first minimum point of $f$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore we need to apply our transformations to the point $(\tfrac{\pi}{6},-1)$.
  We transform the $y$-coordinate by $\times -2$ and then $+3$, therefore the transformed $y$-coordinate is $-1\times-2+3=5$.
  We transform the $x$-coordinate by $\times\tfrac{1}{1/2}$.therefore the transformed $x$-coordinate is $\tfrac{\pi}{6}\times2=\tfrac{\pi}{3}$.
  Therefore $\answer{\text{the first maximum of }g(x)\text{ has coordinates }(\tfrac{\pi}{3}, 5).}$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{A1A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$
